consumer_secret = ''

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit = True, wait_on_rate_limit_notify = True)

Writing a JSON file storing all the tweets¶

In [ ]:
tweet = []
tweet_dict = {"tweet_id" :[], "tweet_status" :[],
              "full_text" :[], "retweet_count": [], "favorite_count" : []}
for ids in enumerate(df.tweet_id):
    try:
        status = api.get_status(ids[1], tweet_mode='extended')
        
        tweet.append(status)
        tweet_dict["tweet_status"].append(status)
        tweet_dict["tweet_id"].append(status.id)
        tweet_dict["full_text"].append(status.full_text)
        tweet_dict["retweet_count"].append(status.retweet_count)
        tweet_dict["favorite_count"].append(status.favorite_count)
    except:
        pass

Issues within the Tweeter Archive DataFrame:¶

Tidiness Issues

  • T-1 denominator of 10 and the numerators could all be in one column
  • T-2 dog stages need to be in one single column (doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo)
  • T-3 it's not clear if the tweet is the original satus or a retweet of something else, so we need to add a column for Retweet (Yes/No)

Quality Issues

  • Q-1 too many NaNs in (in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id, retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id, retweeted_status_timestamp)
  • Q-2 source column is not clear and we need to extract the exact source like iPhone, etc.
  • Q-3 for Dos Stage and Name, for missing values, "None" is used rather than NaN
  • Q-4 timestamp is not standard, so we could change it to a standard format of Date-time
  • Q-7 after replacing None with NaN, we see that a lot of Dog Stages are missing!
  • Q-9 All other ID fileds are also need to be converted into String like in_reply_to_status_id
  • Q-10 It appears that we have inconsistency in extracting the ratings (the numinators). Sometimes the digits after decimal point is extracted

Define¶

will be working with df_clean

418

As we can see from the code above, there are 418 mentions of the words [doggo, puppo, floof, pupper]. So we need to:

  • first change the title of floofer to floof(er)
  • find the ones that are missing in the df file (418 - 394 = 24) are still left without a dog stage

create a list of all records in the Original Data Farme that have at least one of the doggo,puppo,floof,pupper titles in the fileds

Finding the index of 3 different lengthes!

To check whether having a dog_stage label have any positive or negative (non-directional) impact on retweet_count, or favorite_count), we test the null hypothesis below:

The null hypothesis is that there is no statistically significant difference between the population mean of the retweet_count of the records with a dog stage label and that of the rest of the data frames(not having any dog stage label):

$$\large H_0: \mu_D = \mu_N$$

So, the alternative hypothesis is:

  • The population mean of the records with a dog_stage label is significantly different than that of the rest with no dog stage labels: $$\large H_a: \mu_D \neq \mu_N$$

Where:

  • $\large H_0$: the Null Hypothesis;
  • $\large H_a$: the Alternative Hypothesis;
  • $\large \mu_D$: Dog stage label;
  • $\large \mu_N$: No dog stage label;

The proposed Statistical Test¶

Knowing our null and the alternative hypothesis, we need a rigorous statistical test to decide whether we reject or retain the null hypothesis. We need a Two Samples test, a comparison of data from one sample to data from a different sample to determine if the two populations they came from are the same.

Here, we use t-Test for Independent Means. According to this link the assumptions for a t-test for Independent Means are listed below:

  • Interval or ratio scale of measurement (approximately interval)
  • Random sampling from a defined population
  • Samples are independent; no overlap between group members
  • Scores are normally distributed in the population
  • Population variances are equal
In [332]:
print ('Standard Deviation of retweet_count for no_dog_stage_list set:',
       no_dog_stage_list.retweet_count.std())

print ('Standard Deviation of retweet_count for dog_stage_list set:',
       dog_stage_list.retweet_count.std())

print ('Population Mean of retweet_count for no_dog_stage_list set:',

In [335]:
import scipy.stats as stats

statistic,pvalue = stats.ttest_ind(dog_stage_list.retweet_count,
                                   no_dog_stage_list.retweet_count, nan_policy='omit')
print ('pvalue = ', pvalue)

pvalue =  0.003115986588672567

So, it shows that we can reject the null hypothesis because the p-value is less than 0.05 and indeed it is far below that number. So, statistically there is a significant difference between the number of retweets based on whether or not the dog has a dog stage label.

I believe this finding is significant, because it might bring a very interesting insight to WeRateDogs, they know, if they could make sure that they assign a dog_stage to the dog for which they are going to post a status, it may generate more retweets and likes!
